Review dimension: UI/UX
Severity: high
File: src/app/dom-builders.ts:131-245
Title: ARIA menu pattern incomplete: no role=menu/menuitem, no aria-controls, no focus management, no arrow-key nav

Finding:
The trigger uses aria-haspopup='true' and toggles aria-expanded, but: (1) it has no aria-controls pointing to the menu id, so assistive tech cannot associate the button with its popup; (2) the .row-menu container has no role='menu' and the items have no role='menuitem' (they are a plain div containing an <a> and <button>s), so screen readers do not announce a menu or menu-item semantics; (3) focus is not moved into the menu when it opens (neither the button click nor the contextmenu handler calls .focus()), so keyboard/screen-reader users are left on the trigger; (4) there is no Arrow Up/Down/Enter/Escape keyboard navigation between items (only default Tab order, which is non-standard for a menu). This degrades the experience for assistive-tech users below the expected ARIA Authoring Practices Guide menu-button/menu pattern.

Fix instructions (follow exactly; make targeted, minimal changes):
In src/app/dom-builders.ts makeRowMenu, complete the ARIA menu pattern. (a) Give the menu a stable id (e.g. `menu.id = 'row-menu-' + <unique per row>`) and set `btn.setAttribute('aria-controls', menu.id)`. (b) Set `menu.setAttribute('role', 'menu')`. (c) Set `role='menuitem'` on each appended action element (the Download <a> and each makeActionButton result). (d) On open (inside openMenu, after revealing the menu), move focus to the first menuitem: `const first = menu.querySelector('[role=menuitem]'); first?.focus();`. (e) Add a keydown handler on the menu that implements Arrow Down/Up to move focus among menuitems (wrap around), Enter/Space to activate the focused item (default behavior already does this for button/a, so mainly preventDefault for arrows and move focus), and Escape to close and return focus to the trigger button (call closeMenu() then btn.focus()). Keep the existing close-on-document-click and the existing item click handlers intact; this is purely additive aria attributes + focus/arrow-key handling. Update src/app/render-browse.test.ts only if any existing assertion checks attribute sets that would conflict (none currently do).

## Review Feedback History (please address all items)
Attempt 1: The test file doesn't exist or hasn't been updated to cover the ARIA improvements. The fix instructions specify updating tests only if needed, but without seeing the actual test changes, I cannot verify if the new ARIA attributes and focus management are properly tested. I need to review the actual test file `src/app/render-browse.test.ts` to assess whether the ARIA improvements (role=menu/menuitem, aria-controls, focus management, arrow-key navigation) are covered by appropriate tests. Without test coverage verification, the implementation may have regressions or incomplete testing.
Attempt 2: The test file src/app/render-browse.test.ts already contains comprehensive tests for all ARIA menu pattern improvements specified in the fix instructions. The 14 tests in the 'ARIA menu pattern & keyboard navigation' describe block (lines 1525-1767) cover: aria-controls + stable menu id, role=menu on container, role=menuitem on action elements, focus management on open, arrow-key navigation with wrap-around, arrow keys calling preventDefault, and Escape returning focus to trigger. The tests are well-written, independent, and follow existing patterns. However, the implementation in src/app/dom-builders.ts has NOT been updated to implement these ARIA improvements, causing all 14 ARIA tests to fail. The tests serve as a specification for the desired behavior, but the makeRowMenu function needs to be updated to add: (a) menu.id generation and aria-controls attribute, (b) role='menu' on the menu container, (c) role='menuitem' on each action element, (d) focus management on open, and (e) arrow-key navigation handler. No existing tests conflict with the new ARIA attributes.
Attempt 3: The test file src/app/render-browse.test.ts contains comprehensive and well-structured tests for the ARIA menu pattern improvements. The 14 tests in the 'ARIA menu pattern & keyboard navigation' describe block (lines 1559-1767) correctly cover: (a) stable menu id + aria-controls pairing, (b) role='menu' on container, (c) role='menuitem' on all action elements for both files and folders, (d) focus management on open via both button click and right-click, (e) ArrowDown/ArrowUp navigation with wrap-around, (f) preventDefault on arrow keys, and (g) Escape closing menu and returning focus to trigger. These tests follow existing patterns, are independent with proper beforeEach cleanup, and accurately pin the WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices menu-button/menu contract. However, the implementation in src/app/dom-builders.ts has NOT been updated to implement ANY of the ARIA improvements, causing all 14 new tests to fail. The tests serve as a correct specification for the desired behavior but cannot pass without the corresponding source changes.
Attempt 4: The test file src/app/render-browse.test.ts contains 14 comprehensive and well-structured tests for the ARIA menu pattern improvements in the 'ARIA menu pattern & keyboard navigation' describe block (lines 1553-1769). These tests correctly cover: (a) stable menu id + aria-controls pairing (3 tests), (b) role='menu' on container + role='menuitem' on all action elements for files and folders (3 tests), (c) focus management on open via both button click and right-click (2 tests), (d) ArrowDown/ArrowUp navigation with wrap-around + preventDefault (5 tests), and (e) Escape closing menu and returning focus to trigger button (1 test). The tests follow existing patterns, are independent with proper beforeEach Escape cleanup, and accurately pin the WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices menu-button/menu contract. However, the implementation in src/app/dom-builders.ts has NOT been updated to implement ANY of the required ARIA improvements: (1) no stable menu.id or aria-controls attribute on the trigger button, (2) no role='menu' on the .row-menu container, (3) no role='menuitem' on the Download <a> or Delete/Move/Copy <button> elements, (4) no focus() call on the first menuitem in openMenu(), (5) no keydown handler on the menu for ArrowUp/ArrowDown focus navigation or Escape-to-trigger focus. All 14 new tests fail. The tests serve as a correct specification for the desired behavior but cannot pass without the corresponding source changes to makeRowMenu.

